  <h2>A Community, Not a Conference</h2>
  <p>Christ the Reconciler is a residential intentional community on sixteen acres in Elgin, Texas. We share daily prayer, meals, and work. We welcome guests for retreats. We produce teachings, podcasts, and resources for Christians everywhere who believe that the hostility fracturing the Body of Christ is not inevitable — and that Jesus' prayer for unity can actually be answered.</p>

  <p>We are not a new denomination. We are not a parachurch organization running programs. We are {{ copy.traditions }} living together, disagreeing honestly, and choosing not to be enemies. We are rooted in the ancient Christian faith and accountable to recognized leaders across the traditions we represent.</p>

  <a class="btn" href="#">What We Believe</a><a class="btn" href="#">Our Friends and Collaborators</a>
</div>

<div class="block">
  <h2>The Problem is not Division. The Problem is Hostility.</h2>
  <p>Hostility between followers of Jesus runs rampant.</p>

  <p>We express contempt for one another from the pulpit. Outbursts of anger explode on social media. Even acts of physical violence are not unheard of. The world watches and writes off our witness of Jesus.</p>
</div>

<div class="block">
  <h2>Jesus' answer to hostility is Reconciliation</h2>
  <p>Reconciliation is a series of actions that removes hostility in a relationship, repairs the damage it caused, and restores the God-intended unity.</p>
  <p>The God-intended unity for His people is for us to enter into the unity of the Trinity!</p>
  <p>Jesus made this clear in his one prayer for us, recorded in John 17:</p>
  <blockquote>
    <p>I pray also for whoever will believe in me through their message, so that they all will be one, Father, just as you are in me and I am in you.</p>
    <p>May they also be one in us so that this world will believe that you sent me into this world.</p>
    <p class="citation">Jesus in John 17</p>
  </blockquote>

  <h3>We are called to live out this prayer</h3>
  <p>At Christ the Reconciler, we are called to live out this prayer. Or more accurately - to strive towards living out this prayer. We do this through a rule and a way of life, both rooted in John 17 and both available to anyone who wants to take Jesus' prayer seriously.</p>
  <div class="cards">
    <div class="card">
      <h3>The Rule: A Statement of Personal Devotion</h3>

      <p>Anyone, anywhere, can make this commitment — five concrete renunciations of the hostilities that divide the church, and five concrete commitments to the unity Jesus prayed for. It is not a statement of intent. It is a description of how you will actually act.</p>

      <a class="btn" href="#">Read the Statement</a>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h3>The Way of Life: Five Practices</h3>
      <p>These are the outward rhythms of a community shaped by John 17 — prayer, reconciliation, formation, hospitality, and work. You don't have to live in Elgin to practice them.</p>
      <a class="btn" href="#">The Five Practices</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>

